default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the absence of almost any policy or action for people with dementia 
defaultin the developing world the difficulty in identifying what can be done is: just where do we start
default?
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThree priorities for the developed world to assist are clear.  The funding of research into prevention
default,
default treatment and care is one.  Such research may well be
default undertaken in the developed world but it is also important 
defaultto grow research capacity in
default low and middle-income countries - particularly when evaluating care models.  A second is raising awareness - which amongst other things will help to reduce the levels 
defaultof stigma experienced by people with dementia.  
default(The G8 Declaration recognised the need for greater respect and dignity for those affected by dementia and for global efforts to reduce stigma, exclusion and fear.)  
defaultThe third is creating comprehensive care m
defaultodels suitable for the developing world, supported by research which identifies how this needs to differ from care models in the developed world.
default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis would assist the work already being undertaken by the developing world where strategies to combat dementi
defaulta are being devised eg in Mexico and Peru; and in Pakistan where training programmes for GPs and social workers are being put together.  Capacity building and awareness are the two main challenges.
default4.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor capacity building ADI has developed two successful pro
defaultgrammes.  One is ‘Alzheimer’s University’ for emerging associations which takes place each year in London.  Alzheimer’s Society has always been involved in this and is supported by other developed associations in Europe and North America.  
default4.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe second prog
defaultramme is ‘twinning’, in which a developed association works with a developing association
default.  A
defaultlzheimer’s Society twinned
default 
defaultwith 
defaultthe Indian association
default resulting
default in an office in New Delhi being opened, to co-ordinate activities, raise awareness and promote the
default organisation with the Federal Government.  Funding for the 
defaultDementia India 
defaultreport was also found in the UK but more importantly that project was directed by the 10/66 group at Kings College, London (see 6.3).  Wi
defaultthout the twinning programme that report wou
defaultld not have been
default published. Other twinning programmes were set up between, for example, Australia and Pakistan, Netherlands and Indonesia and between Canada and Trinidad &amp; 
defaultTobago
default.
default4.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultResearch within the developing world is essential to assist awareness and 
defaultcapacity building.  This can be founded upon work already done, eg care related (where much work has been done in the UK, facilitated by Alzheimer’s Society) and how care may vary between cultures (where the 10/66 Group has done some work).  Prevention res
defaultearch is also important and recent evidence suggesting that risk factors can be modified, and that these factors vary from country to country (largely lifestyle related) again suggests that this is undertaken within the low and middle-income countries.
default4.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo 
defaultpromote the work that needs to be done ADI is now seeking to start a global awareness programme.  This is an ambitious target but it has been greatly assisted by actions in the UK.  The raised level of dementia awareness in this county, prompted by Alzheim
defaulter’s Society, has led the British government to implement a comprehensive dementia strategy and in 2012 the Prime Mi
defaultnister issued a challenge to ALL
default government departments to seek ways to support the needs of people living with dementia.  
defaultTo date, DFID has
default still to do so. 
defaultWith the UK now in the cha
defaultir of G8, Mr Cameron convened
default a conf
defaulterence in London this year on
default 11
defaultth
default December to discuss the issue and there will be a further three conferences arranged next year.  We regard this as hugely important and indica
defaulttive of the important role played by Britain in the dementia challenge.
default  However, the challenge goes beyond the G8 countries, making DFID’s involvement essential.
default4.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDFID’s lack of response to th
defaulte Prime Minister’s challenge
default 
defaultis 
defaultdisappointing.  Even small 
defaultinterventions
default by DFID could be significant in
default raising awareness, building capacity and facilitating research.
default4.9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSuch support would almost certainly have to be undertaken in conjunction with, or advised by, specialist a
defaultgencies – three
default of which are based in Lo
defaultndon, namely: the 10/66 Group (based at Kings College, London); Alzheimer’s Disease International, possibly the single biggest source of information on dementia in the developing world through its 80 member countries; and Alzheimer’s Society which has expe
defaultrience in developing awareness;  researching dementia cause, cure, care and prevention; and providing support services in the UK.  It has also worked with and supported ADI – particularly in India.
default4.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAll three agencies would welcome a close working relations
defaulthip with DFID to enable UK development aid to be directed towards the dementia challenge.
